{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nOperation certificates become asymmetric on the foundation substrate (namespace `rebar.opcert.v1`), signed by an environment's Ed25519 key and verifiable by anyone against its public key, binding the ticket/state so they cannot be replayed. Environment-key rotation is in scope here too (folded in from former task 5893): it REUSES the era-scoped key-validity mechanism the identity epic shipped in `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` (validity as commit-ancestry positions `added_at_commit`/`revoked_at_commit`, compared with `git merge-base --is-ancestor`) and the shared-schema verdict `key_not_valid_at_era` — applied to the environment keyring, not a new wall-clock scheme.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Op-certs are produced/verified via the foundation substrate with an Ed25519 environment key (namespace `rebar.opcert.v1`); a test asserts a cert signed by env E verifies against E's public key and fails against a different key.\n- [ ] The certificate subject binds `{ticket id, material fingerprint, merged-log position}` (the `(commit, intra_idx)` position model the substrate already uses); a test asserts it cannot be replayed onto a different ticket or a mutated state.\n- [ ] Environment-key rotation reuses `attest/authorship.py`'s commit-ancestry era validity for the env keyring (no new wall-clock scheme); a test asserts a cert from a key valid at its era verifies while one past its rotation does not, surfacing the shared `key_not_valid_at_era` verdict."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783962731821016001,"uuid":"aec6faa2-1eba-443b-adfc-9e0c3427e956"}